
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `lsb_release` baraye peyda kardan etela'at dar morede pakhsh (distribution) Linux shoma, mesle esm va version estefade mishavad.  Be zaboon sade, mige shoma az che distroye Linux estefade mikonid.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `lsb_release -a`  --> 📜 Namayesh hameye etela'at (version, description, ID, va digar chiz-ha).
    🔹 `lsb_release -d`  --> 📝 Fagat description distro ro neshon mide.
    🔹 `lsb_release -v`  --> 🔢 Fagat version distro ro neshon mide.
    🔹 `lsb_release -i`  --> 🆔 Fagat ID (identification) distro ro neshon mide.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ lsb_release -a

    🔹 Namayesh hameye etela'at distro.

    $ lsb_release -d

    🔹 Fagat description distro ro neshon mide.  Meslan: "Description: Ubuntu 20.04.3 LTS"

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ lsb_release

    🔹 Agar bedune gozine ejra beshe, etela'at asasi distro ro neshon mide (meslan version).  Age etela'at kam bood az `-a` estefade konid.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `lsb_release` command is used to display information about your Linux distribution, such as its name and version. Simply put, it tells you which Linux distro you are using.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `lsb_release -a`  --> 📜 Show all information (version, description, ID, and other things).
    🔹 `lsb_release -d`  --> 📝 Only show the distribution's description.
    🔹 `lsb_release -v`  --> 🔢 Only show the distribution's version.
    🔹 `lsb_release -i`  --> 🆔 Only show the distribution's ID (identification).

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ lsb_release -a

    🔹 Shows all the distribution's information.

    $ lsb_release -d

    🔹 Only shows the distribution's description. For example: "Description: Ubuntu 20.04.3 LTS"

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ lsb_release

    🔹 If executed without any options, it shows basic distribution information (like the version). If the information is limited, use `-a`.
